{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> μάντῐς</b>, ὁ, <br /> <i>genitive</i> εως, <i>Ionic dialect</i> ιος; <i>vocative</i> μάντῐ: <i>plural</i>, <i>genitive</i> μάντεων (written μαντειον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 12.503)\">Refs</a>]; <i>dative</i> μάντεσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 545: also _feminine_, _accusative_ _sing._ μάντιδα δάφνην “App.Anth.” 6.122 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; <i>nominative</i> <i>plural</i> μάντιδες Suid. see at {Σίβυλλα}:— <b>diviner, seer, prophet</b>, ἀλλ᾽ ἄγε δή τινα μ. ἐρείομεν ἢ ἱερῆα ἢ καὶ ὀνειροπόλον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.62, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 17.384 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; μάντι κακῶν <b>prophet</b> of ill, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.106 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; with the Greek armies, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Simonides Lyricus 94, “IG” 12.929.129: distinguished from χρησμολόγος, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.1; μ. ἀνήρ 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 6(5).51 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of Apollo, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1202, “Ch.” 559, “Eu.” 169 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ὁ μάντις μάντιν ἐκπράξας ἐμέ, of Apollo and Cassandra, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ag.” 1275 \">Refs</a>]; of the Pythian priestess, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Eu.” 29 \">Refs</a>]; of Amphiaraus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Th.” 382, etc.: with _dative_ _person_, ὁ Θρῃξὶ μ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 1267 (of Dionysus), compare “Or.” 363: with _accusative_ _neuter_ _pronoun_, μάντις.. οὐ καλὸς τάδε [prev. author] “Heracl.” 65: as _feminine_, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Ag.” [same place], 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 472 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 239; μ. κόρα 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 11.33. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <i>metaphorically</i>, <b>presager, foreboder</b>, μ. εἴμ᾽ ἐσθλῶν ἀγώνων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1080 (Lyric poetry), compare “Ant.” 1160, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 402; οὐδεὶς μ. τῶν μελλόντων 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 1419 (_anapaest meter_); γνώμη δ᾽ ἀρίστη μ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 757. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3>  <i>adjective</i>, τοῦδε μάντεως χοροῦ of this <b>prophetic</b> band, uncertain in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 113. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> a kind of <b>grasshopper</b>, the <b>praying mantis, Mantis religiosa</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 10.18, 1st c.AD: Dioscorides (Dioscurides) Medicus “Eup.” 1.149. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>green garden-frog, Rana arborea</b>, so called as <b>predicting</b> the weather, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.AD(?): Hesychius Legal icographus \">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> a kind of <b>cabbage</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Nicander Epicus “fragment” 85.7. \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__V</b></Level2> applied to comets, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Hermes Trismegistus cited in 5th c.AD: Stobaeus, Joannes 1.21.9. (Deriv. from μαίνομαι by 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 72a, 72b.) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G8254","accentedUnicode":"μάντις","shortDef":"a clairvoyant","mediumDef":"a clairvoyant","stepGloss":"a clairvoyant","stepTransliteration":"mantis","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}